---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="DynamoDB Partitioning & Adaptive Capacity"
  description="Interactive visualization of DynamoDB hash partitioning, auto-splits, adaptive capacity, burst capacity, and throughput allocation"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: "Home", href: "/" },
    { label: "DynamoDB", href: "/dynamodb/" },
    { label: "Partitioning", href: "/dynamodb/partitioning/" }
  ]}
>
<div class="viz-container">
  <header class="viz-header">
    <h1>⚡ Partitioning &amp; Adaptive Capacity</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">How DynamoDB Distributes Data and Eliminates Hot Partitions</p>
  </header>

  <!-- Overview -->
  <section class="overview-section">
    <div class="overview-card">
      <p>
        DynamoDB uses <strong>hash partitioning</strong> to distribute items across storage nodes. Each item's
        <em>partition key</em> is hashed to determine which partition stores it. When a partition grows too large
        (&gt;10 GB) or too hot (exceeds throughput), DynamoDB <strong>automatically splits</strong> it. Since 2018,
        <em>adaptive capacity</em> ensures hot partitions borrow unused throughput from cold ones — eliminating the
        classic hot partition problem. Unused throughput is <strong>banked for 5 minutes</strong> as burst capacity.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Partition Key Hashing -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>🔑 Partition Key Hashing</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Type a partition key to see which partition it maps to. Items with the same partition key always land in the same partition.</p>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="calc-input-row">
        <input type="text" id="keyInput" placeholder="Type a partition key (e.g. user-1001, order-5522)" class="key-input" autocomplete="off">
        <button id="hashBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">Hash</button>
      </div>
      <div class="calc-result" id="calcResult"></div>
      <div class="calc-formula" id="calcFormula"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="partitionCanvas" width="820" height="340"></canvas>
    </div>
    <div class="partition-legend" id="partitionLegend"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- Partition Map: Insert & Split -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>📦 Partition Map &amp; Auto-Split</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Insert items and watch partitions fill up. When a partition exceeds its capacity, DynamoDB automatically splits it into two.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <div class="slider-group">
        <label>Initial Partitions: <strong id="partCountLabel">4</strong></label>
        <input type="range" id="partSlider" min="2" max="8" value="4" class="slot-slider">
      </div>
      <button id="insertRandomBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">➕ Insert 10 Items</button>
      <button id="insertHotBtn" class="action-btn kill-btn">🔥 Insert Hot Key (x50)</button>
      <button id="resetPartBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="flow-status" id="splitStatus">
      <span class="status-badge idle" id="splitBadge">Ready</span>
      <span class="status-text" id="splitStatusText">Insert items to see partitions fill and auto-split</span>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="splitCanvas" width="820" height="400"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="failover-timeline" id="splitTimeline"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- Explain: Partition Splits -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-grid">
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📏 Size-Based Splits</h3>
        <p>
          Each partition can hold up to <strong>10 GB</strong> of data. When a partition approaches this limit,
          DynamoDB splits it into two new partitions, redistributing the hash range. The split happens
          <em>transparently</em> — your application never sees it. The old partition's token range is divided
          at the midpoint.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>🔥 Throughput-Based Splits</h3>
        <p>
          If a partition consistently receives more than <strong>3,000 RCU or 1,000 WCU</strong>, DynamoDB
          may split it to spread the load. After adaptive capacity (2018), this is less aggressive —
          the system first tries to <em>borrow throughput</em> from underutilized partitions before splitting.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Adaptive Capacity -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>🧠 Adaptive Capacity</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Hot partitions automatically borrow unused throughput from cold ones. No more throttling from uneven access patterns.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <div class="slider-group">
        <label>Table WCU: <strong id="wcuLabel">400</strong></label>
        <input type="range" id="wcuSlider" min="100" max="1000" step="100" value="400" class="slot-slider">
      </div>
      <button id="startAdaptiveBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ Simulate</button>
      <button id="resetAdaptiveBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="adaptiveCanvas" width="820" height="380"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="adaptive-info" id="adaptiveInfo">
      Click "Simulate" to watch adaptive capacity reallocate throughput in real-time
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Explain: Adaptive Capacity -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-card highlight-card">
      <h3>💡 The End of Hot Partitions</h3>
      <p>
        Before 2018, DynamoDB divided table throughput <strong>evenly</strong> across partitions. A table with
        400 WCU and 4 partitions gave each partition exactly 100 WCU. If one partition got 200 writes/sec, it was
        <em>throttled</em> — even though the table had 200 WCU sitting idle on cold partitions. <strong>Adaptive
        capacity</strong> fixed this: hot partitions can now use up to the <em>entire table throughput</em>,
        borrowing from cold partitions instantly. Combined with <strong>burst capacity</strong> (5 minutes of
        banked unused throughput), throttling from uneven access is essentially eliminated.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Burst Capacity -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>⏱ Burst Capacity</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Unused throughput is banked for up to 5 minutes. Watch the burst bucket fill and drain during traffic spikes.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="startBurstBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ Simulate</button>
      <button id="resetBurstBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="burstCanvas" width="820" height="300"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="burst-info" id="burstInfo">
      Click "Simulate" to watch burst capacity bank and spend unused throughput
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RCU/WCU Allocation -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>📊 Provisioned vs On-Demand</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Compare how throughput is allocated under provisioned mode (with auto-scaling) vs on-demand mode.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <label class="toggle-label">
        <input type="checkbox" id="modeToggle">
        <span class="toggle-switch"></span>
        <span>On-Demand Mode</span>
      </label>
      <button id="startModeBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ Simulate Traffic</button>
      <button id="resetModeBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="modeCanvas" width="820" height="320"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="mode-info" id="modeInfo">
      Choose a mode and simulate a realistic traffic pattern with spikes
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Explain: On-Demand vs Provisioned -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-grid">
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📋 Provisioned Mode</h3>
        <p>
          You specify <strong>RCU and WCU</strong> per table. Auto-scaling watches CloudWatch metrics and adjusts
          capacity with a <em>2-minute cooldown</em>. Good for <strong>predictable workloads</strong> — cheaper
          than on-demand when you can estimate traffic. Downside: sudden spikes hit before auto-scaling reacts.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>⚡ On-Demand Mode</h3>
        <p>
          DynamoDB <strong>instantly</strong> accommodates up to <em>2x the previous peak</em> traffic. No capacity
          planning needed. You pay per request (~5x more expensive per unit than provisioned). Ideal for
          <strong>unpredictable workloads</strong>, new tables, or when you'd rather pay more than get throttled.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- GSI & LSI -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>🗂 GSI &amp; LSI Partitioning</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Global Secondary Indexes are separate tables with their own partitions. Local Secondary Indexes share the base table's partition.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="showGsiBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">Show GSI</button>
      <button id="showLsiBtn" class="action-btn step-btn">Show LSI</button>
      <button id="resetIndexBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="indexCanvas" width="820" height="420"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="failover-timeline" id="indexTimeline"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- Explain: GSI vs LSI -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-grid">
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>🌐 Global Secondary Index</h3>
        <p>
          A GSI is essentially a <strong>separate DynamoDB table</strong> maintained by the system. It has its own
          partition key (and optional sort key), its own partitions, and its own throughput. Writes to the base
          table are <em>asynchronously replicated</em> to the GSI. This means GSIs are <strong>eventually
          consistent</strong> — you cannot do strongly consistent reads on a GSI.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📌 Local Secondary Index</h3>
        <p>
          An LSI shares the <strong>same partition key</strong> as the base table but allows a different sort key.
          Data lives in the <em>same partition</em> as the base table item. LSIs support <strong>strongly consistent
          reads</strong> but count against the partition's 10 GB limit. You must create LSIs at table creation
          time — they cannot be added later.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <footer class="viz-footer">
    <p>Based on <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/HowItWorks.Partitions.html" target="_blank">AWS DynamoDB Documentation</a> and <a href="https://www.amazon.science/publications/amazon-dynamodb-a-scalable-predictably-performant-and-fully-managed-nosql-database-service" target="_blank">Amazon DynamoDB: A Scalable, Predictably Performant, and Fully Managed NoSQL Database Service (2022)</a></p>
  </footer>

  <div class="share-buttons">
    <span>Share this visualization:</span>
    <a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Interactive%20visualization%20of%20DynamoDB%20partitioning%20and%20adaptive%20capacity&url=https://systeminternals.dev/dynamodb/partitioning/" target="_blank" class="share-btn">𝕏 Twitter</a>
    <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/sharing/share-offsite/?url=https://systeminternals.dev/dynamodb/partitioning/" target="_blank" class="share-btn">in LinkedIn</a>
    <a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/submitlink?u=https://systeminternals.dev/dynamodb/partitioning/&t=Interactive%20DynamoDB%20Partitioning%20%26%20Adaptive%20Capacity%20Visualizer" target="_blank" class="share-btn">🟧 Hacker News</a>
  </div>
</div>
</BaseLayout>

